Scraping Google Scholar for appeals cases

Sarah Cohen

6/18/2020

Setup

Well be using two main libraries to get and parse the web pages: httr (which manages requests from the Web), and rvest (which takes the raw page and turns it into a parsed document, and lets you use XPATH to traverse it.

Well also be doing a couple of things you may not have seen before:

Creating a function

Sometimes, when youre going to do the same thing over and over, and its a little complex, its easier to bundle up the instructions into a function, just the way we did with the omelet in class. Were going to put the part of the program that pulls out elements of each case into a row for a data frame into a function.

The good part is that you can test it on just one item. The bad part is that its a little more difficult to troubleshoot. Ill usually try to get it to work on one or two examples, then wrap function around those instructions. In this case, Ive already done the wrapping.

Using loops

We need two loops in this case: one that will go through each page of the results, and another that will go through each item within each page. Youll see how to do this later.

Libraries and such

Here are the libraries you need. The Options. command just turns this request into something that is identified as coming from a regular browser, not some anonymous program. It sometimes matters and sometimes doesnt.

One thing to be careful of try to test carefully, because Google will cut you off for a while if you try too many requests. I think its maybe about 5000 in a certain amount of time, but youll find thats really easy to do.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE, eval=FALSE)

Setting up the query and finding the pieces of the page

Well be using the Inspector in Chrome to figure out how to get the information we need from the query. I often then use Chrome Scraper to test the XPATH Im going to use. Ill walk you through that separately.

In general, though:

  • What are the parameters of the query?
  • What is the path to each element you want to keep?
  • What is your strategy for getting the docs you want?

This time, well do it in two steps. The first one is to get a list of all of the cases. The second is to go through those cases and download them into a data frame. Theres a chance that will have to be done in batches if Google cuts us off. Im not sure whether they will or not. Well add a one-second delay between each time we go to Google to hopefully avoid that.

After looking at the Inspector, there are five elements we need to tell Google Scholar. You can find them in your inspector under Network, and select the Headers from the main document:

Here they are put into a list:

my_query <- list ( "hl"="en",
                   "as_sdt" = "ffffffffffffe04", 
                   "q" = '"school resource officer"', 
                   "start" = 0, 
                   "as_ylo" = "2010")

I dont know what all of them stand for, but hl is the language; as_sdt is the list of courts (in this case, I chose all state courts), the query that you type into the Google form (notice the weird quotes because we want the whole phrase), what page you want (start at 0), and what year you want to start from (I chose 2010)

Notice that there are 728 results, and we get 10 per page. That means we need to have a list of pages that goes something like (0, 10, 20, .. 720) , telling the search engine to start displaying each page of records using the number of the item.

Heres how you do that:

pages <- c(0:72)*10
items <- c(1:10)

Finally, we need an empty data frame to hold the information from each case. Although our

df_master <- tibble ( page_num = integer(),
                      line_num = integer(), 
                      case_name = character(),
                      case_reference = character(),
                      case_snippet = character(),
                      case_link = character(),
                      case_html = character()
                      )

Thats all of the things that wont change. All thats left is the function itself!

The function

Heres the function I wrote. I cant break it up into explained pieces, so well walk through it together. You need three things to make it work:

  • A row in the form of an rvest object, which is a parsed version of the HTML for one case
  • The page number youre working with
  • The item number youre working with

(We really dont need the last two things, but its useful to keep track of what youve done and what you havent, so adding together page + item gives you a unique identifier.)

In general:

  • html_node picks out a piece of the row based on the XPATH shown. In the first case, for instance, its the URL as identified by the first link tag (a) followed by its href attribute. This function only picks out ONE item, not a group of them. If there are more than one, it picks out the first.

  • html_text returns just the text, not the encoding or tags of that element.

  • as.character converts the complex rvest object into plain HTML text.

This simply takes what we do in Chrome scraper and puts it into code that you can use over and over

get_row <- function ( rowdata, page, item ) {

    tmplink <- 
       rowdata  %>%                        # start with the item 
       html_node( xpath=".//a/@href") %>%  # extract  the first  <a> tag's "href" attribute
       html_text() %>%                     # get that as text
       stringr::str_extract("case=\\d+") %>%    # use a regular expression to get just the case number
       paste0("https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?", .)   #add the actual link before that.
    
    
    #the text of the link
    tmpname <- 
      rowdata  %>%
      html_node (xpath = ".//a") %>%                  #get the text of the link, not its URL
      html_text()
    
    tmpref  <- 
      rowdata %>%
      html_node (xpath = ".//div[@class='gs_a']") %>%  
      html_text()
    
    tmpsnippet  <- 
      rowdata %>%
      html_node(xpath = ".//div[@class='gs_rs']") %>%  
      html_text() 
    
    #this preserves our original row, in case we need to get back to it someday.
    
    tmphtml <- 
      rowdata  %>%
      as.character()       #get all of the full HTML from the item, in case ...
    

    # now turn it into a data frame - just use tibble because it creates better data frames.
    answer <- tibble( page, item, tmpname, tmpref, tmpsnippet, tmplink, tmphtml)
    
    #send the answer back to the main program.
    return (answer)
  
  
}

Lets try it out with one page and one item:

In this case, well get the page that starts with the 31st row, then well try to get information out of the 8th row from that page.

NOTE: Google Scholar has pretty strict daily limits on queries, so its likely this would have to be done over a few days. This example uses a saved copy of the page in case it doesnt work when you try it. If you want to try it on your own, save a page of the Scholar results in a file called sro_p4.html in your default directory and itll use that in case it doesnt work.

Testing one page and one item

First, well request the page, and parse it to get the HTML object that can be traversed using XPATH (or css selectors, which I dont understand)

testpage = 30
testitem = 8

#change the start parameter of the query:
my_query$start <- testpage
#this makes a request from the Web
response  <- httr::GET("https://scholar.google.com/scholar", query=my_query)
#this turns it into an HTML object with XPATH and css trees

if (status_code(response)==429) {
  full_page <- read_html("sro_p4.html")
} else {
  full_page <- read_html(response)
}

Now we will split it into its rows using the XPATH that we see in the Chrome Scraper, then call the function to get our data frame. We should get 10 nodes returned, 1 for each case on the page.

case_list <- html_nodes( full_page, xpath='//div[@class="gs_r gs_or gs_scl"]')

length(case_list)
## [1] 10

Yay! There are 10!

Now well try the function:

#choose the row from the list of caes based on the row number we saved earlier
raw_case <- case_list[testitem]
row_data <- get_row ( raw_case, testpage, testitem)

glimpse(row_data)
## Rows: 1
## Columns: 7

## $ item       <dbl> 8

## $ tmplink    <chr> "https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=449507703397
## $ tmphtml    <chr> "<div class=\"gs_r gs_or gs_scl\" data-cid=\"OEAWGL-4YT4J\

That seemed to work!

In the next step, well loop through every item on every page to add all of them to the data frame. (In knitting this document, this part wont run. Instead, its loading the result so that we dont get in trouble with Google.)

Loop through the pages and rows

There are two strategies for this - you can either save the pages temporarily into a folder, then go through them to parse them, or do it all at the same time.

DONT RUN THIS PART ON YOUR OWN unless youre going to live with what Google gives you including a lot of errors if youve overstepped your limits. Just in case, I commented out the save command that youd use to make sure you never have to do it again. (Its ignored during knitting)

#copy the structure of our data frame, so we don't worry that it's not empty
case_data <- df_master

#just try two pages at first.

for (p in pages) {
    
    #ALL OF THIS IS EXACTLY WHAT WE DID BEFORE  
    my_query$start <- p
    #this makes a request from the Web
    response  <- httr::GET("https://scholar.google.com/scholar", query=my_query)
    full_page <- read_html(response)
    case_list <- html_nodes( full_page, xpath='//div[@class="gs_r gs_or gs_scl"]')
    
    #now get each row's data and stuff it into a data frame.
    for (i in items)  {
      raw_case <- case_list[i]
      row_data <- get_row ( raw_case, p, i)
    
      #add it to our data frame
      case_data <- rbind (case_data, row_data)  
      
    }
    
    #wait a second! This makes your computer slow down so it doesn't upset Google.
    Sys.sleep(1)
   
}

# save(case_data, file="google_case_sro.Rda")

The errored out at the end because there were only 8 cases on the last page thats ok. To do it more accurately, youd do this:

  for (i in length(case_list)) ...

But it doesnt really matter.

Get the documents

First, there is something weird about the output of the last step, which Ill ignore the variables ended up with the names made inside the function, not the names of the master data frame we set up. I dont know why, so well just live with it.

It may be that you dont even need all of the documents you might just want to work from the list you created in a spreadsheet or an Airtable. But if you wanted to load them all into something else, you could just download each document using the link. I recommend creating a docs folder to keep them in, and save each document using a part of its link. That way you know whether you already have it.

To loop through a data frame, you have to select it by row number, then pick out the rows variables that you want.

For example, Ill take a random sample of 10 documents:

cases <- case_data %>%
  sample_n (25)


for (rownum in 1:nrow(cases)) {
  
  url <- as.character(cases[rownum, "tmplink"])
  
  save_name <-  paste0 ( "data/case_", 
                         str_extract (url, "\\d+$"), 
                         ".html"
                        )
  
  download.file(url, save_name)
  
  Sys.sleep(.5)
  
  
}
